{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583146"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:09:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:09:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2086"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2086"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.08,0.54,0.14,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2086"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78366"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2086"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2086"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63728"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"992"},{"type":"tags","id":"4556"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9906"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"211"},{"type":"contributions","id":"224"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26862"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26921"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78366"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring exercise, oxygen demand increases in active muscle groups. Several physiological changes occur to facilitate oxygen delivery to these tissues.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following increases the delivery of oxygen from haemoglobin to active tissues?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased 2,3-diphosphoglycerate concentration","Decreased partial pressure of carbon dioxide","Increased blood temperature","Increased blood pH","Decreased tissue metabolic rate"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe haemoglobin-oxygen dissociation curve describes the relationship between oxygen partial pressure and haemoglobin saturation. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased blood temperature\u003C/strong\u003E shifts this curve to the right, reducing haemoglobin\u0027s affinity for oxygen and promoting oxygen unloading to tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased 2,3-diphosphoglycerate concentration\u003C/strong\u003E shifts the curve left, increasing haemoglobin\u0027s oxygen affinity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased partial pressure of carbon dioxide\u003C/strong\u003E shifts the curve left (Bohr effect)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased blood pH\u003C/strong\u003E shifts the curve left, increasing oxygen affinity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased tissue metabolic rate\u003C/strong\u003E reduces the oxygen gradient between blood and tissues, decreasing oxygen delivery\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring exercise, increased temperature, carbon dioxide, and acidity all promote oxygen unloading to metabolically active tissues through right-shift of the dissociation curve.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Increased blood temperature shifts the haemoglobin-oxygen dissociation curve to the right, reducing haemoglobin\u0027s affinity for oxygen.","Right-shift of the haemoglobin-oxygen dissociation curve facilitates oxygen unloading to metabolically active tissues.","2,3-diphosphoglycerate, pH, temperature and carbon dioxide are key modulators of haemoglobin\u0027s oxygen affinity."],"references":["Barrett K, Barman S, Brooks H, Yuan J, Ganong W. Ganong\u0027s review of medical physiology. 25th ed. McGraw-Hill Education / Medical; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63728"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2086"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63728"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T13:25:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T14:10:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2086"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78366"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null